SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 397
By Akbari
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Sondra Denise Keys-
Wade.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the untimely passing of our friend and
former colleague Sondra Denise Keys-Wade; and
WHEREAS, Sondra Keys-Wade was an extraordinary individual who personified
excellence, success, and service; she approached life lovingly and faced daily living with fierce
optimism and was the epitome of God's true and faithful servant; and
WHEREAS, born on June 11, 1974, Ms. Keys-Wade was the daughter of Kay Miller
Cook and David Lee Keys, Sr.; she attended Memphis City Schools elementary and secondary
schools and was the first homecoming queen at John P. Freeman Junior High; and
WHEREAS, after graduating from Central High School, Sondra Keys-Wade attended
Dillard University before transferring to the University of Memphis, where she was a member of
two honor societies and a student delegate to the Tennessee Black Legislative Caucus Retreat;
and
WHEREAS, she developed an interest in and love for politics early in life and served as
an intern to Lois DeBerry, State of Tennessee Representative for District 91 and former
Speaker Pro Tempore of the Tennessee House of Representatives; she also volunteered with
the Clinton/Gore 1996 presidential campaign; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Keys-Wade earned her Juris Doctor degree from Vanderbilt University
School of Law, receiving the Bennett Douglas Bell Memorial Award upon graduation; during her
time at Vanderbilt, she studied abroad at Cambridge University in England, volunteered with the
Juvenile Practice and Legal Aid clinics, and served on the Faculty-Student Relations
Committee; and
