WHEREAS, following graduation, Sondra Keys-Wade returned home to Memphis, and
her professional path continued as Assistant City Attorney with the City of Memphis and then as
an associate and lobbyist with the Harold Ford Group; she later accepted the position of
Regional Manager for the Tennessee Human Rights Commission, an independent State agency
that investigates allegations of discrimination for State agencies; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Keys-Wade returned to Nashville, where she joined the General
Assembly's Office of Legal Services, in which position she gained the respect and trust of
legislators and staff on Capitol Hill; she thereafter resumed private practice with one of the
nation's leading law firms, Baker, Donelson, Bearman Caldwell & Berkowitz, working as a
government relations attorney in the firm's State Public Policy Group; and
WHEREAS, as a consultant at Anderson Consulting, LLC, she developed and
implemented comprehensive legislative, administrative, and regulatory strategies; she also
served as Director of Government Affairs for Stand for Children, representing its interests before
state and local public policy groups, and her final career calling brought her to Middle
Tennessee State University's Office of General Counsel, where she worked in the position of
Assistant General Counsel; and
WHEREAS, throughout her career, her professional affiliations included membership in
the Tennessee Bar Association, the Napier-Looby Bar Association, the Vanderbilt University
Alumni Association, and the Tennessee Alliance of Black Lawyers; she was a gubernatorial
appointee to the Tennessee Department of Human Services Board of Appeals and a member of
the Tennessee Bar Association Leadership Law Class of 2011; and
WHEREAS, ever focused on community service, Sondra Keys-Wade volunteered her
time on the Board of Directors for the Nashville Conflict Resolution Center, and she was a proud
member of 100 Black Women of Middle Tennessee; she served on the Grants Review
